    "summary": "The Babylonian Captivity (597–538 BC) was the period during which the Jewish elite — nobility, priests, craftsmen, and intellectuals — were deported from Judah to Babylon by Nebuchadnezzar II after his conquests of 597 and 586 BC. Estimates of the deported population range from 10,000 to 20,000; the poor agricultural population largely remained. The [[event:1909|Destruction of Solomon Temple]] in 586 BC, which ended the Temple-based sacrificial religion, created an existential religious crisis that the exiled community addressed through intensive literary and theological activity.\n\nThe Babylonian exile was arguably the most formative period in the development of Judaism as a religion. Without the Temple and its sacrifices, Jewish identity coalesced around scripture, Torah study, synagogue worship, and Sabbath observance — practices that could be maintained without a homeland. Many scholars believe that major portions of the Hebrew Bible (Torah, Prophets, Psalms, Lamentations) were written or substantially edited during the exile, with Ezekiel, Deutero-Isaiah, and other prophetic texts addressing the theological crisis of national catastrophe. The [[event:1913|Fall of Babylon to Persia]] liberation decree by Cyrus the Great in 538 BC allowed the exiles to return, but Babylon's Jewish community remained significant for centuries.",
